accessibility.text: Use of trigonometry in our lives

Weather forecasting: Trigonometry is used in weather forecasting to track the movement of storms and to predict the path of hurricanes. For example, trigonometry is used to calculate the angle of the wind at different altitudes or to determine the distance between two weather stations.

Archaeology: Trigonometry is used to measure the angles and distances between objects in archaeological sites. This information can be used to reconstruct the layout of the site and to identify the features that were present.

Cartography: Trigonometry is used to create maps. By measuring the angles and distances between points on the Earth's surface, cartographers can create accurate representations of the Earth's surface.
